<h2>Culture and Tradition of  The Tiv</h2>
<p>Culture is generally refers to the way of life of people. The people of Tiv have some of the most unique cultures in Nigeria. Their traditions have been passed from one generation to another. I would be considering some of these under the following subheading:</p><div class="k6wSyrzo" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 8 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="7361956093"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<ul>
<li>Marriage</li>
<li>Dressing</li>
<li>Music</li>
<li>Food</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p><div class="TNf4qwJi" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 14 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="5845037909"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<h2><strong>Marriage</strong></h2>
<p>Marriage in Tivland is rooted in the rich culture of the Tiv people. There are four ways marriage is sealed in Tiv land;</p>
<ul>
<li>Marriage by exchange</li>
<li>Marriage by capture</li>
<li>Marriage by purchase</li>
<li>Marriage by bride price</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Mariage by exchange</strong> (<em>yamshe</em>): In this type of marriage, the man looking for a wife simply approaches another man looking for a wife also. The marriage will only come to fruition when both parties have women to exchange; such as daughters or wives.</p><div class="IoKWzwpU" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 16 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="9431422522"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p><strong>Marriage by capture</strong> (<em>kwase-ngohol</em>): Here a woman is forcefully snatched from her husband during travel. This type of marriage was rampant during the early Tiv migration and it was responsible for majority of the inter-clan wars. Another form of marriage by capture occurs when a man visits another country to lure a woman away from the country.</p>
<p>When the man visits another country he stays in the house of a man whose mother is also from his country. He then sends his friends or relatives to look for unmarried girls for him.</p><div class="Ip6Z8IjF" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 18 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="2960688417"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>After he selects the girl he likes, he would then visit the house of the girl.</p>
<p>Also the men who make up this group would go to different communities to perform dances. When ladies come over to watch them, they are usually attracted to some of the men.</p><div class="mumZ31mV" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 300X600 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:inline-block;width:300px;height:600px"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="8444795376"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>Eventually the men would take some of these ladies as their wife back to their country. This process of obtaining a wife is called <em>Iye</em>; a honorable marriage of capture as opposed to the forceful marriage of capture described above.</p>
<p><strong>Marriage by Purchase</strong>: This type of marriage is known as <em>kwase u sha uikya</em>. Here girls are captured as slaves and married off.</p><div class="ROonpp28" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 22 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="5863728512"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p><strong>Marriage by bride price</strong>: This is the marriage currently been practiced in Tivland. It became prominent as a form of marriage during the European administration, when they decided to abolish other forms of marriage.</p>
<p>The European administration insisted that men should pay bride price before he can take any girl as his wife.</p><div class="q5yp4eFa" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 24 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="2674442489"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>The man would continuously send gifts to the girl and her family. When the girl’s family is satisfied with his gifts, he is then informed on come and pay the bride price for the girl.</p>
<p>Most of the time, the couples would elope without paying the bride price. The bride price is paid later when the man is ready.</p><div class="306ChgbD" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 26 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="4122221684"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Music and Dance</h2>
<p><iframe title="Tiv, Benue state. Nigerian dance" width="780" height="585" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/m91x9N1Org4?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe></p><div class="ZN9NE4kS" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 28 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="5672156828"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>Music is part of the culture of the Tiv people. They have being able to advance a form of communication that blends music intricately with it. This communication promotes the use of various traditional musical instruments such as;</p>
<p><strong>Kakaki:</strong> An instrument which is used to pass important messages to the community. This message could be the crowning of the King, the birth of the King’s son, the marriage of the King’s son or during an attack by opposing community. Members of the community are told to gather at the village square.</p><div class="C5oUbWdJ" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 30 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="9674092963"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p><strong>Ilyu</strong>: This is an instrument made of light wooden material which is also used to gather elders for a meeting with the King. It is also used to announce the death of someone in the community.</p>
<p><strong>Indyer</strong>: This is a special musical instrument made from mahogany trunk. It is used during festivals such as the Yam Festival to pass information as regards the festival to the people. It is also used to announce the success of a good harvest year.</p><div class="xich72yM" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 32 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="4846160314"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p><strong>Gbande</strong>: This is a large musical instrument played by young men of the community during festival. The gbande produces strong rhythms when played and it beats carry with it messages to the people. It is significant during occasion like coronation and death of the King.</p>
<p><strong>Adiguve</strong>: This instrument resembles the violin and it is one of the popular musical instruments used by the Tiv people. During festival, the Adiguve is played to the admiration of all. It is also symbolic during the death of an elder in the community.</p><div class="S9uEaSvR" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 34 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="6823927719"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2><strong>Tiv Dressing Code</strong></h2>
<p>Since time immemorial, the Tiv people have perfected the art of weaving; a craft passed from generation to generation. Tiv people favor their traditional attire to any other form of attire due to the strong cultural identity it commands.</p><div class="IYLDsvFn" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 36 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="6193372322"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>The <em>anger </em>is Tiv most popular form of attire. It is made up of white and black stripes woven together to form a beautiful design.</p>
<p>There is <em>Tugudu</em> which is used strictly for burying dead ones. The women of Tiv like to put on a special fabric known as <em>Ivvavtyo</em> which is worn during important occasions.</p><div class="83yh5rvC" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 38 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="5967670295"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>Other fabrics used by the Tiv people are Lishi, Gbev-whaa, Godo, Gurugu, Chado, Deremen and Gbagir.</p>
<p>The Tiv people apply a very painstaking process in making their fabrics. It takes about a day for one person to weave, dye and prepare the fabric for sale.</p><div class="zvhwX1pE" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 40 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="6856357935"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>The fabric is greatly patronize by many people and it has helped to boost the economy of the state.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p><div class="Xk7jqr13" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 42 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="1836853596"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<h2>Burial in TV Land</h2>
<p>The Tiv people attach great significance to the burial of their loved ones. The burial is steeped in their local customs.</p>
<p>The process starts with the sending of messages to <strong><em>Takurudu</em></strong> who is regarded as the ancestor of the Tiv people. This is usually done with the aid of musical instrument such as Idya or Ilyu.</p><div class="hboiWXBp" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 44 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="1604031252"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>He is informed of the death of the person and told to await the arrival of the dead in the ancestral world.</p>
<p>On the day of the burial, the corpse would be washed by elderly woman and wrapped in <em>Anger, Tugudu or Gbagir</em> attire.</p><div class="SniDDuDB" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<!-- 46 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     data-ad-slot="6473214554"
     data-ad-format="auto"
     data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></div>
<p>Usually the dead is buried within 24 hours and no coffin is used.</p>
<h3><strong>Watch the Video of a Documentary about the Tiv people below</strong></h3>
<p><iframe title="Tiv People" width="780" height="585" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Kt3Q1H0DCY8?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe></p><div class="e7ylccxB" style="clear:both;float:left;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9755093768544960"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
